{"cursor":"4609","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Trust, but verify' is a form of advice given which recommends that while a\nsource of information might be considered reliable, one should perform\nadditional research to verify that such information is accurate, or trustworthy.\nThe original Russian proverb is a short rhyme which states, ÐÐ¾Ð²ÐµÑÑÐ¹, Ð½Ð¾ Ð¿ÑÐ¾Ð²ÐµÑÑÐ¹\n(doveryai, no proveryai).\n\nSuzanne Massie, a writer on Russia met with President Ronald Reagan many times\nbetween 1984 and 1987. She taught him the Russian Proverb, Doveryai\nno Proveryai (Trust but Verify) advising him that \"The Russians like to talk in\nproverbs. It would be nice of you to know a few. You are an actor â you can\nlearn them very quickly\". Suzanne Massie speaking on the 22nd Episode of the\ntelevision documentary, Cold War (TV series). The proverb was adopted as a\nsignature phrase by Reagan, who subsequently used it frequently when discussing\nU.S. relations with the Soviet Union.\n\nAfter Reagan used the phrase to emphasize \"the extensive verification procedures\nthat would enable both sides to monitor compliance with the treaty\", at the signing of the INF Treaty, on 8 December 1987, The Intermediate Nuclear Force Treaty (INF) aimed to eliminate short\nand medium range nuclear weapons from their respective national arsenals (Watson\n2011). Watson described it as a \"written embodiment of Gorbachevâs policies and\npersonality based on a life spent in and out of the Soviet Union.\" his\ncounterpart General Secretary Mikhail Gorbachev responded: \"You repeat that at\nevery meeting,\" to which Reagan answered \"I like\nit.\" [http://www.reagan.utexas.edu/archives/speeches/1987/120887c.htm\n\"Remarks on Signing the Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces Treaty\"], 1987-12-8.\nRetrieved on 2009-4-8. While Reagan quoted\nRussian proverbs, Mr. Gorbachev quoted Ralph Waldo Emerson.\n","linknr":130,"url":"Trust,_but_verify","recorded":1374546356,"links":["/w/in